ngland","Up Holland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Shenton, Leicestershire, England":"Shenton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1 November 1165–December 1197":"1 november 1165–december 1197","1152–1202":"1152–1202","1163–Female":"1163–Overleden","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1177–1212":"1177–1212","1197–1242":"1197–1242","1130–1180":"1130–1180","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1 November 1197":"1 november 1197","1 November 1165":"1 november 1165","December 1197":"december 1197","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","1130":"1130","1163":"1163","1152":"1152","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1202":"1202","1212":"1212","1177":"1177","Stanton Harcourt, Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Up Holland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Shenton, Leicestershire, England":"Shenton, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1 November 1165–December 1197":"1 November 1165–December 1197","1152–1202":"1152–1202","1163–Female":"1163–Deceased","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1177–1212":"1177–1212","1197–1242":"1197–1242","1130–1180":"1130–1180","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1 November 1197":"1 November 1197","1 November 1165":"1 November 1165","December 1197":"December 1197","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","1130":"1130","1163":"1163","1152":"1152","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1202":"1202","1212":"1212","1177":"1177","Stanton Harcourt, Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Up Holland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Shenton, Leicestershire, England":"Shenton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Harcourt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the places in Eure and Calvados named Harcourt, from Old French <i>cour(t)</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (see   Court  ) with an obscure first element. This surname is very rare in France.","English: habitational name from either of two places in Shropshire named Harcourt. The one near Cleobury Mortimer gets the name from Old English <i>heafocere</i> ‘hawker, falconer’ + <i>cot</i> ‘hut, cottage’; the one near Wem has as its first element Old English <i>hearpere</i> (see   Harper  ).","History: The surname of French origin (see 1 above) is listed along with the equally rare or even extinct variants or altered forms <i>Haraucourt</i>, <i>Herancourt</i>, and <i>Héraucourt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Court","meanings":["English: topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>curt</i>, <i>court</i> ‘large house’ (a word of the same ultimately Latin origin as 2 below), denoting someone who lived or worked in a manor house or castle, a courtly retainer.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (from Latin <i>cohors</i>, <i>cors</i>, genitive <i>cohortis</i>, <i>cortis</i> ‘court, farmyard, enclosure’).","English and French: nickname for a physically small man, or ironically for a large man, from the adjective Middle English <i>curt</i>, Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘short, small’ (from Latin <i>curtus</i> ‘curtailed, truncated, cut short, broken off’). Compare French   Lecourt  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Harcourt was born on 1 November 1165, in Leicestershire, England, her father, Sir Ivo Yves d’Harcourt, was 35 and her mother, Agnes de Braose, was 35. She had at least 1 son with Mathew de Holland. She died in December 1197, in Up Holland, Lancashire, England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1 November 1165–December 1197":"1. november 1165–detsember 1197","1152–1202":"1152–1202","1163–Female":"1163–Surnud","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1177–1212":"1177–1212","1197–1242":"1197–1242","1130–1180":"1130–1180","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1 November 1197":"1. november 1197","1 November 1165":"1. november 1165","December 1197":"detsember 1197","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","1130":"1130","1163":"1163","1152":"1152","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1202":"1202","1212":"1212","1177":"1177","Stanton Harcourt, Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Up Holland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Shenton, Leicestershire, England":"Shenton, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshi